<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> [Problem C] Let <m>T_1=\rho_{(u_1, \alpha_1)}</m> and let <m>T_2=\rho_{(u_2, \alpha_2)}</m> be two rotations in <m>\mathbb R^3</m>.  Show that there exists <m>u\in \mathbb R^3</m>  and an angle <m>\alpha</m> such that the composition <m>T_1\circ T_2</m> is a rotation <m>\rho_{(u,\alpha)}</m>. (In short: composition of two rotations in <m>\mathbb R^3</m> is a rotation. This is a trivial statement in <m>\mathbb R^2</m>, but it is not as trivial in <m>\mathbb R^3</m> when we rotate around different pole vectors.)
    </p>
  </statement>  
  <hint>
    <p>
        Use Euler's theorem to translate into a statement about matrices.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>


