<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> [Problem E] 
        Euler's theorem describes all matrices in <m>O_3</m> with determinant <m>1</m> as being rotation matrices. We can understand thus the operators given by such matrices in a geometric manner: rotate in a plane perpendicular to some pole vector (that is an eigenvector for the matrix), leaving the pole vector unchanged. 
    </p>

<p> If <m>A\in O_3</m> with <m>\det(A)=-1</m>, can you describe geometrically (in a somewhat similar manner) the operators  <m>T(x)=Ax</m> given by these matrices?  How do these operators act on points in <m>\mathbb R^3</m>? 
    </p>
  </statement>  
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> [Problem F]  Let <m>r_1</m>, <m>r_2</m> and <m>\rho</m> denote isometries in <m>\mathbb R^2</m> such that:
    </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p> <m>r_1</m> is a reflection in a line <m>\ell_1</m></p>
        </li>
        <li>
         <p><m>\rho</m> is a rotation of angle <m>\theta</m> (not necessarily though the origin)</p>
      </li>
      <li>
      <p> <m>r_2</m> is a reflection in a line <m>\ell_2</m> </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
     Prove that the composition <m>r_1 \rho r_2</m> is a rotation or a translation. 
    </p>
  </statement>  
  <solution>
    <p>
        Note that rotations and translations are precisely the isometries of <m>\mathbb R^2</m> that are orientation preserving. 
    Remember that isometries form a group and think about how one can decide orientation preserving or reversing.
      </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>




<exercise>
