    </p>
  </statement>  
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p> [Problem H] Working in the group <m>T</m> of all translations in <m> \mathbb R^2</m> (it is a group with respect to composition):  Note that, if <m>a</m> is a nonzero vector in <m>\mathbb R^2</m>, then <m>\langle t_a\rangle\cong C_{\infty}</m> because <m>t_a</m> has infinite order. (Recall that <m>C_{\infty}</m> is the cyclic group generated by an element of infinite order. It is isomorphic to <m>\mathbb Z^+</m>.)  
    </p>
     <p> 
      Now prove: If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are two linearly independent vectors in <m>\mathbb R^2</m>, then <m>\langle t_a, t_b\rangle \cong C_{\infty}\times C_{\infty}</m> (or <m>\mathbb Z\times \mathbb Z</m> if you want.)
Make sure to emphasize in your proof how the hypothesis that <m>a,b</m> are linearly independent is used. 
    </p>
  </statement>  
  <hint>
    <p>
      Use the Product Proposition. Note that <m>(t_a)^n=t_{na}</m>.   
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>



